/ORGANIZATION> were investigating the accident. The Independent and Evening Standard newspapers on Monday reported a disagreement had developed between the two captains over which vessel had the right of way under the central span of <LOCATION> Southwark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>, where the collision occurred. `` It seems that both captains thought that they were in the right, but technically the actions of both could be held up to scrutiny,'' the Standard quoted an unnamed river authority source as saying. But <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON> of Tidal Cruises said that although smaller craft usually stick to the side arches, <PERSON> Faldo </PERSON> was correct to move through the center Sunday because of tide conditions. `` We do not know what went wrong,'' she said. `` Our captain was acting totally correctly.'' Police said they listened tape-recorded radio traffic between the captains of both vessels and shore control for clues into the cause of the crash. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard declined to comment on the newspaper reports.
